  "prompt": "Does a user always need to keep the data \u2018ON\u2019 for outgoing/incoming calls on Jio network?",
  "response": "No, a user **does not** always need to keep data 'ON' for outgoing/incoming calls on the Jio network.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Voice over LTE (VoLTE):** Jio primarily uses VoLTE technology for voice calls. VoLTE allows voice calls to be made over the 4G LTE data network instead of the traditional 2G/3G networks. However, the VoLTE functionality itself does not directly consume your data balance.\n*   **Data is used for VoLTE setup and signaling:** While the call itself doesn't use significant data, a very small amount of data might be used to initially set up the VoLTE connection and for signaling purposes (e.g., call connection and disconnection). This data usage is minimal and usually doesn't significantly deplete your data balance.\n*   **Calls Work Without Active Data Session:** You can still make and receive calls even if you have your mobile data completely turned off, as long as you have an active Jio plan with voice call benefits.\n*   **Wi-Fi Calling:** Jio also supports Wi-Fi calling. If you're connected to a Wi-Fi network, your calls will be routed over Wi-Fi, and you don't need mobile data to be turned on.\n\n**In summary:** You can make and receive calls on the Jio network without keeping mobile data 'ON.' The minimal data needed for VoLTE setup is usually handled without you actively needing to keep the data switch enabled, as long as you have an active voice plan. And if on Wi-Fi calling, mobile data is irrelevant.",
